  "prompt": "Why is sodium hydrogen carbonate soluble in water?",
  "response": "Sodium hydrogen carbonate (NaHCO\u2083), also known as baking soda, is soluble in water due to a combination of factors:\n\n*   **Ionic Nature:** NaHCO\u2083 is an ionic compound composed of sodium cations (Na\u207a) and hydrogen carbonate anions (HCO\u2083\u207b). Ionic compounds are generally more soluble in polar solvents like water because the water molecules can effectively interact with and stabilize the ions.\n\n*   **Ion-Dipole Interactions:** Water is a polar molecule, meaning it has a partial positive charge on the hydrogen atoms and a partial negative charge on the oxygen atom. When NaHCO\u2083 is added to water, the water molecules surround the ions. The partially negative oxygen atoms in water are attracted to the positive Na\u207a ions, and the partially positive hydrogen atoms are attracted to the negative HCO\u2083\u207b ions. These attractions are called ion-dipole interactions.\n\n*   **Hydration:** The ion-dipole interactions lead to the hydration of the ions. Hydration is the process where water molecules surround and solvate the ions. This process releases energy (exothermic), which helps to overcome the lattice energy holding the Na\u207a and HCO\u2083\u207b ions together in the solid crystal structure of NaHCO\u2083.\n\n*   **Entropy Increase:** When NaHCO\u2083 dissolves, the ions are dispersed throughout the water, leading to an increase in entropy (disorder). Nature favors processes that increase entropy, and this contributes to the solubility of NaHCO\u2083.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nThe solubility of sodium hydrogen carbonate in water is a result of:\n\n1.  The ionic nature of the compound.\n2.  Strong ion-dipole interactions between the ions and water molecules.\n3.  The release of energy during hydration.\n4.  An increase in entropy upon dissolution.\n\nThese factors work together to make the dissolution of NaHCO\u2083 in water a thermodynamically favorable process, resulting in its solubility.",
